<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-416-074  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 416 074.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  April 11 1990 n130 p24(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business andamp; Computer Publications(England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>BT plans network management system. (British Telecom)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   British Telecommunications PLC (product development).andO;Topic:     ConnectivityNetwork ManagementProduct DevelopmentMultivendor SystemsCommunications Service SuppliersCooperation.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>BT plans network management system British Telecom has mapped out ambitiousplans to launch a range of products and services intended to simplify the waycorporates control and manage their computer and data networks.andM;BT says that the network management system, called Concert, will adopt openstandards, allowing customers to manage and control their multi-vendornetworks in a uniform way.andP;  These networks could include public and privatevoice and data systems.andP;  &quot;Customers will have an overall view of theircomplete resources,&quot; commented David Dey, managing director of BT'sCommunications Systems division.andM;The telecommunications giant says Concert's technology and interfaces arebeing implemented in key networking products and services which make up BT'sCustomer Managed Communications family.andM;BT has set up a Network Management Liaison Group with a number of suppliers,including IBM and DEC, in a bid for interaction between different managementsystems through open interfaces.andP;  It will also collaborate with vendorsthrough its membership of the OSI Forum.andM;The first products are scheduled for release in mid 1991, following trialimplementations towards the end of 1990.andP;  Fault diagnosis, cost savings andimproved performance are said to be among the potential benefits of Concert.andM;* British Telecom is to go through a major internal reorganization which,according to newspaper reports, could lead to as many as 10,000 job losseseach year over the next three years.andM;Graeme Odgers, BT's managing director, is the first casualty of therestructure, which is expected to lead to between 2,000 and 4,000 job cutsamong managers.andP;  It is said that the move, to be implemented over the nextyear, will prepare BT to compete in international markets.andO;</TEXT></DOC>